title: Node 1
summary: I have three tattoos already, but they are all astronomy or physics related. I had the idea that my next tattoo would be more organic.

title: Node 2
summary: I began sketching some ideas of what this organic tattoo might look like. I knew I liked flowers, but perhaps organic patterns as well.

title: Node 3
summary: The second sketch I did was more rough_

title: Node 4
summary: The third sketch I did was exploring more patterns_

title: Node 5
summary: I chose dahlias as my flowers for my wedding, which took place on July 21, 2012.

title: Node 6
summary: After my wedding, it hit me that I wanted my tattoo to be meaningful, and that if I chose dahlia flowers, my tattoo could be a reminder of my wedding day and the commitment that I share with my husband.

title: Node 7
summary: I did a lot of research and found many pictures of other people_s flower tattos. These were inspirational as I was thinking about mine.

title: Node 8
summary: I spent some time sketching ideas. At first I was very interested in incorporating patterns into the tattoo and not just a flower image.

title: Node 9
summary: I tried sketching how the tattoo might lay out on my body.

title: Node 10
summary: I did some sketches exploring different patterns.

title: Node 11
summary: I found this piece of art online, and immediately loved it and thought it was the perfect starting point for my tattoo.

title: Node 12
summary: I collected many pictures of dahlia flowers online that I thought were good as references.

title: Node 13
summary: I finished the first flower by removing the extra graphics from the original artwork I had found, and retracing it to make it my own.

title: Node 14
summary: This photo I found of a dahlia online was the one I decided to trace for my second flower.
